summary: 11/20/1991: A helicopter crashed in the Martuninsky area of the Nagorno-Karabakh region in the republic of Azerbaijan.  The helicopter was carrying official delegates from Azerbaijan, Russia, and Kazakhstan, who were engaged in the peace process between Armenia and Azerbaijan; all 23 passengers and pilot were killed.  Sources originally reported that the helicopter crashed due to fog; however, follow-up inspections revealed a hole in the Mi-8 chopper that resembled a missile strike.  No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
target1: Multinational members of a peace delegation
motive: Specific motive is unknown; however, the passengers were on a fact-finding mission as part of a strategy to defuse hostilities in the area
addnotes: Azerbaijan accused Armenia of being responsible for the incident, but this was not confirmed
scite1: "Helicopter Crashes in Caucasus Killing More Than 20 People," Associated Press, November 20, 1991.
scite2: Brian Friedman, "Gorbachev Says Republic Officials Fail to Endorse Union Treaty," Associated Press, November 25, 1991.
scite3: "Missile Suspected In Soviet Crash," The Washington Post, November 22, 1991.

target1: Afiyaddin Jalilou, Deputy to Parliament Chairman
Building housing offices of General Prosecutor

location: The centre of Stepanakert, in Nagorno-Karabakh Republic
summary: 3/22/2000: Arkady Gukasyan, the unofficial president of the Nagorno-Karabakh enclave, was shot and wounded as he was driving home in Stepanakert, in Nagorno-Karabakh Republic, Azerbaijan.  His driver and bodyguard were also injured in the attack.  The former Nagorno-Karabakh Defense Minister Samvel Babayan and his brother, Stepanakert Mayor Karo Babayan, were arrested in connection to the attack.  Government authorities stated that the attack was designed to undermine democratic reform.
target1: Arkady Gukasyan, the unofficial president of the Nagorno-Karabakh enclave
target2: The driver and bodyguard of the unofficial president
motive: Specific motive is unknown, but government authorities state that the incident was designed to undermine democratic reform
scite1: "Gunmen wound president of Nagorno-Karabakh in ambush," Dow Jones International News, March 22, 2000.
scite2: "Attempt on the life of Nagorny Karabakh president," Prime News, March 22, 2000.
scite3: Tigran Liloyan, "2 officials arrested in Karabakh assassination attempt case," ITAR-TASS News Agency, March 22, 2000.

summary: 08/17/2001: A statue of Sheikh Shamil, leader of a 19th-century rebellion against Russian forces, was bombed by an unknown group in Zaqatala, Azerbaijan.
target1: Statue of Sheikh Shamil in Zaqatala, Azerbaijan
propcomment: The pedestal was shattered and the bust cracked from the explosion. The windows of a nearby house and cars were also blown out.
scite1: “Memorial to rebel leader blown up in Azerbaijan,” Associated Press Worldstream, August 18, 2001
scite2: “Police arrest monument bombing suspects," ANS Television, August 17, 2001.
scite3: “Caucasus guerrilla leader's monument blown up in Azerbaijan," ANS Television, August 17, 2001.

summary: 08/19/2001: An attack was launched against the police station in Zaqatala, about 350 kilometers north of Baku, Azerbaijan. Five policemen were wounded in the attack by alleged Avar nationalists.
motive: The perpetrators were trying to free comrades arrested at the beginning of August 2001.
propcomment: The police station sustained minor damage.
scite1: “Itar-Tass Russia and CIS news digest of August 19,” TASS, August 19, 2001.
scite2: “Attacks in N.Azerbaijan Attributed to Avar Separatists,” Kommersant, August 22, 2001.

summary: 08/30/2001: A group of unidentified assailants attacked the hotel hosting Deputy Interior Minister Zahid Dunyamaliyev and First Deputy Prosecutor-General Ramiz Rzayev in Zaqatala, Azerbaijan. No injuries occurred.
scite1: “Senior Azeri northern district officials attacked,” ANS-ChM Television, August 30, 2001.

location: This incident occurred on the ninth kilometer of the Zaqatala-Balakan road in Zaqatala District.
summary: 09/28/2001: An unknown group attacked the traffic police post number 718 on the ninth kilometer of the Zaqatala-Balakan road in Zaqatala District, Azerbaijan. They used grenades and assault rifles, wounding one person and damaging six cars. One of the perpetrators was killed in the attack as well. No group claimed responsibility for the attack.
target1: Police post 718 in Azerbaijan on the Zaqatala-Balakan road in Zaqatala District.
addnotes: The dead body of Anvar Osmanov, a resident of Katex village, an assault rifle and one large-calibre fire arm owned by the criminals was found at the scene.
scite1: "One Dead in Attack on Police Checkpoint in Northern Azerbaijan,” Azerbaijani TV 1, September 29, 2001.

summary: 05/03/2002: An unknown perpetrator threw a grenade at the residence of Nasimi Musaffar Oglu Mehraliyev in Baku Azerbaijan. Mehraliyev was seriously injured in the attack and require hospitalization. No group claimed responsibility for the attack.
target1: Nasimi Musaffar Oglu Mehraliyev, a resident of Baku's Narimanov District
weapdetail: One grenade was thrown at the victim's house
addnotes: The victim lived in a neighborhood that housed Azerbaijan's head of state.
scite1: “Man Injured in Grenade Attack Near Azerbaijani Presidential Residence,” Lider TV, May 3, 2002.

summary: 04/10/2007: Militants set fire to and destroyed a Catholic church in Baku, Azerbaijan, but there were no reports of casualties.  No one claimed responsibility for the incident.
scite1: Staff, “Azeri Imam Condemns Arson Attack on Catholic Church,” Baku Turan, April 11, 2007.

location: The incident occured at the Abu-Bekr mosque.
summary: 08/17/2008: On Sunday, at an undescript time, in Baku, Azerbaydzhan Territory, Azerbaijan, a grenade exploded during evening prayers at a packed mosque. Three were killed and 10 were injured. There were no claims of responsibility.
target1: The target was the Abu-Bekr mosque.
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: The explosive used was a hand grenade.
propcomment: The extent of the property damage is unknown.
scite1: Associated Press, "Mosque Attacked in Azerbaijan," Associated Press, August 17th, 2008.
scite2: Lexis Nexis, "Azerbaijan Security Officers Arrest 18 Suspects In Baku Mosque Explosion," Interfax, September 8th, 2008.

location: The bombing occurred at a transformer station in Baku, Baki, Azerbaijan.
summary: 08/22/2008: On Friday, in Baku, Baki, Azerbaijan, an improvised explosive device exploded at a transformer station when Bakielektrikshabaka electrical workers attempted to install a new transformer, killing two employees, wounding three others, and damaging the building. No group claimed responsibility, although authorities believed the Forest Brothers were responsible.
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: An improvised explosive device was used in the attack.
propcomment: A building and electrical transformers were damaged in the attack.
scite1: Itar Tass News Agency (Russian Federation), "Two Die, Two Injured in Baku Substation Blast," LexisNexis Academic, Itar Tass News Agency (Russian Federation), August 22, 2008.
scite2: National Counterterrorism Center, "Two Civilians Killed, Three Others Wounded in IED Attack by Suspected Forest Brothers in Baku, Baki, Azerbaijan," Worldwide Incidents Tracking System, January 19, 2010.

location: The attack occured approximatley 150 meters from the victim's home in Baku, Azerbaijan.
summary: 02/11/2009: On Wednesday morning, the chief of the Azerbaijan Air Force, General Rail Rzayev, was shot and killed while on his way to work. General Rzayev was shot in the head when his driver stopped to throw out garbage, approximatley 150 meters from the victim's home. The shooter and weapon type are unknown and no group has claimed responsibility for this attack.
target1: The Chief of the Azerbaijan Air Force
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: An unknown firearm was used in the attack.
propcomment: It Is unknown if the attack caused any property damage.
scite1: Agence France Presse, "Head of Azerbaijani Air Force Shot Dead: Police," LexisNexis Academic, Agence France Presse, February 11, 2009.
scite2: Itar Tass News Agency, "Azerbaijan Air Force Chief Assassinated," World News Connection, Itar Tass News Agency, February 11, 2009.

location: The attack took place in Asadly, Jalilabad, Azerbaijan.
summary: 06/18/2009: On Thursday night at about 2245, in Asadly, Calilabad, Azerbaijan, assailants threw grenades and fired at soldiers and border guards at a border checkpoint, killing one soldier, wounding two border guards and reportedly killing an unknown amount of civilians. No damage was reported and no group claimed responsibility, although it was widely believed the Forest Brothers were responsible.
target1: Soldiers and border guards at a border checkpoint
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: Unknown firearms and grenades were used in the attack.
scite1: National Counterterrorism Center, "One Soldier Killed, Two Border Guards Wounded in Grenade Attack by Suspected Forest Brothers in Asadly, Calilabad, Azerbaijan," Worldwide Incidents Tracking System, November 20, 2009.
scite2: BBC Monitoring Trans Caucasus Unit, "Azerbaijan: Soldier, Several Civilians Said Killed near Iranion Border," LexisNexis Academic, BBC Monitoring Trans Caucasus Unit, June 19, 2009.

summary: 03/03/2014: An explosive device detonated near the People's Front of Azerbaijan Party office in Baku city, Baku district, Azerbaijan. No one was injured in the blast; however, the explosion caused property damage. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
propcomment: A building was damaged in this attack.
addnotes: There is doubt that this incident meets terrorism-related criteria. While some sources indicated that the source of the explosion was a gas leak, other sources noted that there are no gas pipelines in the building's basement. Therefore, it is unknown if the blast was accidental or the result of an attack on the party's office.
scite1: "No casualties reported in blast near Azeri opposition party's office," APA Online, March 3, 2014.

location: The incident occurred in the Garachukhur neighborhood
summary: 11/26/2014: Assailants set fire to a mosque in Garachukhur neighborhood, Baku city, Azerbaijan. A guard was injured in the attack. No group claimed responsibility for the incident; however, security forces attributed the attack to Yekbun.
propcomment: A mosque was damaged in this attack.
scite1: "Azerbaijan detains two suspects over arson attack on mosque in Baku," APA Online, December 1, 2014.
scite2: "Mosque serving as Salafi gathering place set to fire in Azerbaijan," Panorama.am, November 26, 2014.

summary: 12/06/2014: Assailants attacked the house of a Jewish religious leader in Quba district, Quba rayon, Azerbaijan. No casualties were reported. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
propcomment: It is unknown if a house was damaged in this attack.
scite1: "Program Summary: Baku ANS Television Azeri 1700 GMT 09 Dec 14," ANS Television, December 9, 2014.

summary: 05/01/2016: Assailants threw a hand grenade at a police station in Aliabad, Zaqatala, Azerbaijan. One police officer was wounded in the attack. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
scite1: "Grenade attack on village police indicates low-level militant threat in Azerbaijan's northern regions with Sunni ethnic minorities," IHS Global Insight, May 5, 2016.
scite2: "Grenade attack on village police indicates low-level militant threat in Azerbaijan's northern regions with Sunni ethnic minorities," Jane's, May 5, 2016.
scite3: "Grenade Explosion at Police Station," Turan Information Agency, May 2, 2016.

summary: 12/03/2016: Security forces shot and killed a suicide bomber attempting to detonate near a shopping center in Baku, Azerbaijan. The assailant was the only reported casualty. No group claimed responsibility for the incident; however, authorities identified the assailant as Emin Azizagaoglu Jami.
weapdetail: An explosives-laden belt was used in the attack.
scite1: "Azeri Security Forces Kill Suspected Suicide Bomber," Radio Free Europe, December 3, 2016.
scite2: "Azerbaijan's State Security Service says suicide terrorist killed when attempting to blow himself outside shopping center in Baku (Part 2)," Interfax, December 3, 2016.
scite3: "Azerbaijan’s security officers kill attempted suicide bomber in Baku," Ennahar Online, December 3, 2016.
